Hi all, I know things are winding down, but I'm doing research on universities and their relationship with the blockchain industry. What do you all consider to be:

a) the most influential/important/largest projects in the space? I'm thinking, like, actually (currently) large... Coinbase, EF, Binance, entities that employ a lot of blockchain people; and
b) who are the most influential/prolific/important academics in the space?

Just taking a general poll, so there's no real way to be wrong! Have an internal list of academics and projects, but just want to make sure I'm not missing anything obvious  :slightly_smiling_face:

Thanks all!!

Hi <@U016W4S9ZGU>. Undergrad researcher here. Basically within ASU Blockchain Research Lab the most popular topics are either contributing to core/infrastructure for Ethereum (moreso than Hyperledger) or building applications (in this case, Hyperledger moreso than Ethereum) as it’s easier to get funding for the latter

There is a miscellaneous mix of other projects, like using NuCypher proxy reencryption or building our own platforms, but it’s highly contingent on the research interests of the faculty

Overall although there are academics that make sound open-source contributions as to possible applications and theoretical scaling & security mechanisms, people like <@U0180195551> and Vitalik Buterin are the role models because much of the notable R&D is happening within their organizations

Thanks, <@U017HN6F9NU>!  Super fascinating.  May be interested in connecting to learn more about the ASU blockchain lab—poked around on the site a little but don't know much about it. Appreciate the info!

Thoughts on Polkadot as it relates to ETH or just in general?

I hacked around with it for a weekend, so I can share some of my thoughts. There's probably plenty of misconceptions I'm making since I don't have the deepest of understanding of the protocol and my experience with it is rather brief.

It's a lot faster, more scalable, cheaper gas than ethereum. Time to finality is roughly 5-7 seconds, and the gas price is virtually unnoticeable from my experience with it. It also has the ability for people to build their own blockchains with unique core functionality using substrate, which is something (as I understand it) ETH2 won't necessarily support, though the vast majority of use cases don't need it's own blockhain. It's already out in mainnet after being relatively extensively tested in kusama, so it's cool to see a truly scalable layer one out in mainnet. In contrast, we still don't have to clear a date eth2 mainnet will be live in its full form, though perhaps for good reason because this sort of thing is important to get right early on. 

That being said the amount of parachains it can have is limited to the scalability of the relay chain. The relay chain also introduces some degree of centralization, and ymmv as far as your concern thereof. 

They other thing I did want to mention is that the devX for substrate is pretty bad. Atm the libraries and abstractions are quite clunky and hard to use unless you're quite familiar with the internals and really good at rust.
They also are planning to be very closely integrated with eth using some kind of bridge network, though I haven't looked into it so much.

In general due to the 'build your own blockhain' nature of Polkadot I think it leans towards being more useful for some use cases than others, specifically use cases that a homogenous blockchain like ethereum doesn't handle as well.

I don't think we should be opposed to other layer ones, and I don't think there will eventually be a 'one blockchain to rule them all' kind of situation because each has its own tradeoffs that make it more attractive for some use cases than others, and there are plenty of ways to connect blockchains to each other anyways, so I think it's good for us to keep experimenting with building stuff on other protocols rather than the 'one chain to rule them all' approach.

I accually really like NEAR protocol as an alternative layer one - IMHO its developer experience is probably at least on-par with ethereum and it’s constantly improving. Rust is a much better language for writing smart contracts than solidity because, well, solidity is kind of a mess - basically as if we were using JavaScript on a blockchain.

<@U016Q0F66FM> thank you so much for your in-depth explanation arising from your experience. This is the most valuable piece of information I've read on the topic (as most the other information is from Polkadot). Thank you thank you thank you!
And thanks for the recommend on NEAR.Will look into as well!

thanks <@U017DKW89DW>! Other than the frequency thing, can you elaborate on what was confusing?

Hey, <@U0172BR9Q8H>, I think that the questions were long or were structured in a way that I’m used to. I often had to read them twice to make sure that I was getting the meaning of the question.

For example, “How often do you find it challenging to cycle / bike as often or as far as you would like in a given week?”

I would prefer to the question to be broken down into two separate questions in the following format: “In a given week, how many times did you find it challenging to cycle / bike as often as you’d like”

“In a given week, how many times did you find it challenging to cycle / bike as far as you’d like?”

Hope that helps!
